        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>NAP</strong> stands for <strong>Name, Address, and Phone number</strong> — the standardized trio of business identity data that search engines use to verify and rank local businesses. Google, Bing, and Apple Maps cross-reference NAP across hundreds of sources: your website, Google Business Profile, Yelp, Facebook, and industry directories. When NAP matches exactly everywhere, Google trusts the business is real. Inconsistencies hurt Local Pack visibility.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Consumer trust impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">80% lose trust at inconsistency</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">US data aggregators</div>
            <div class="tms-value">4 major (Data Axle, Localeze, Foursquare, Factual)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">NAP consistency is not glamorous SEO work. But it is foundational. Inconsistent NAP is one of the most common reasons local businesses fail to appear in the Local Pack — and it compounds silently while you work on everything else.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is NAP?</h2>
        <p>NAP is the combination of three pieces of business identity data:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Name:</strong> The exact legal or trading name of your business</li>
          <li><strong>Address:</strong> The physical street address, including unit number if applicable</li>
          <li><strong>Phone:</strong> Your primary business phone number, in a consistent format</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Some practitioners extend this to NAP+W, adding Website URL as a fourth element. The "+" becomes significant when tracking which version of a domain (with or without www, http vs https, trailing slash or not) appears across citations.</p>
        <p>NAP is your business's digital fingerprint. Google crawls thousands of directories and data sources, extracting and comparing NAP information. The more consistently your NAP appears across authoritative sources, the more confident Google becomes that your business genuinely exists at that location — and the more likely it is to surface you in local search results and the Local Pack (the map results that appear above organic results for local queries).</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why exact match matters</div>
          <p>Google's fuzzy matching has improved but is not perfect. "Bob's Plumbing LLC" vs "Bob's Plumbing," "123 Main St" vs "123 Main Street, Suite 4," or "555-123-4567" vs "(555) 123-4567" can all be interpreted as different entities by automated citation aggregation systems. The safest approach: pick one exact format and use it everywhere, copied character-for-character.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why NAP consistency matters for local SEO</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Trust verification for Google.</strong> Consistent NAP across multiple independent sources signals that the business genuinely exists at that location and is reachable. Google cannot verify your business by visiting it — NAP consistency is how it confirms your legitimacy at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Search engine confusion creates ranking problems.</strong> When Google finds "123 Main St" in one listing and "123 Main Street, Suite 4" in another, it cannot always confirm these are the same business. That uncertainty reduces ranking confidence. The business with perfectly consistent NAP beats the inconsistent competitor.</li>
          <li><strong>Consumer acquisition impact.</strong> 93% of consumers report frustration with incorrect information in online directories (BrightLocal). Incorrect phone numbers, old addresses, and wrong hours are not just SEO problems — they are direct revenue loss.</li>
          <li><strong>Data aggregator multiplication.</strong> Four major US data aggregators — Data Axle, Localeze, Foursquare, and Factual — supply business information to hundreds of smaller directories. An error at the aggregator level multiplies across dozens of platforms. Fixing the source fixes the downstream problem at scale.</li>
          <li><strong>Local Pack eligibility.</strong> NAP consistency is a confirmed ranking factor for the Local Pack. A business with inconsistent NAP competes at a disadvantage against a business with identical NAP everywhere, even if all other signals are equal.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How NAP works in local search</h2>
        <p>Google builds what it calls an "entity" — a representation of your business — by aggregating signals from multiple sources. NAP is the identity anchor for that entity.</p>

        <h3>Cross-referencing across sources</h3>
        <p>Google crawls: your website, Google Business Profile, Yelp, Facebook, Yellow Pages, industry-specific directories, news articles that mention your business, and data feeds from the four major aggregators. It compares NAP across all of these. Agreement across sources strengthens the entity. Disagreement weakens it.</p>

        <h3>Data aggregator pipeline</h3>
        <p>The four major US aggregators (Data Axle, Localeze, Foursquare, Factual) maintain business databases that dozens to hundreds of smaller directories pull from automatically. If your data is correct at the aggregator level, corrections propagate forward. If it's wrong there, errors spread. Submitting accurate NAP directly to aggregators is a force multiplier — one correction fixes dozens of downstream citations.</p>

        <h3>Your website as the authoritative source</h3>
        <p>Google treats your own website as a higher-authority source for your NAP than third-party directories. LocalBusiness schema markup on your homepage and contact page tells Google exactly what your official NAP is, in machine-readable format. This is the first place to get right.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Types of NAP issues and their SEO impact</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Issue type</th><th>Example</th><th>SEO impact</th><th>Fix priority</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Business name variation</strong></td>
                <td>"Bob's Plumbing" vs "Bob's Plumbing LLC"</td>
                <td>Entity confusion, reduced ranking confidence</td>
                <td>High — fix at source</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Address format mismatch</strong></td>
                <td>"Ste 4" vs "Suite 4" vs no unit number</td>
                <td>Multiple entity interpretations</td>
                <td>High — standardize format</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Old phone number</strong></td>
                <td>Previous number still on 40+ directories</td>
                <td>Direct revenue loss + trust damage</td>
