                <td>Previous location still active on Apple Maps, Bing</td>
                <td>Local Pack drops, customer confusion</td>
                <td>Critical — full citation cleanup</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td><strong>Duplicate GBP listings</strong></td>
                <td>Two Google Business Profile entries, slightly different NAP</td>
                <td>Self-competition, ranking split</td>
                <td>Critical — merge or remove</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real NAP inconsistency examples and fixes</h2>

        <h3>1. Dental practice standardization</h3>
        <p>A dental practice operated under three name variations across platforms: "Bright Smiles," "Bright Smiles Family Dentistry," and "Bright Smiles Dental." After identifying the official legal name and submitting standardized NAP to the four major data aggregators, then manually correcting the top 20 directory listings, they saw a 2-position Local Pack improvement within 8 weeks. No new links, no content changes — just NAP consistency.</p>

        <h3>2. Plumbing company phone number cleanup</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company changed their main phone number but only updated Google Business Profile and their website. Forty-plus directory listings retained the old number. After a full citation cleanup targeting the aggregators first, their Google Business Profile call volume increased 25%. Callers who had been reaching a disconnected number started reaching the business.</p>

        <h3>3. Law firm relocation</h3>
        <p>A law firm relocating across town updated Google Business Profile, their website, and LinkedIn. For six months, Apple Maps, Bing Places, Yellow Pages, and industry directories displayed the old address. They fell out of the Local Pack during this period — local search traffic dropped 34%. After a full citation cleanup using BrightLocal, their Local Pack position returned within 6 weeks of correction completion.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">NAP vs citation — what is the difference?</h2>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>NAP (the data)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The actual information: name, address, phone</li>
              <li>Your "digital fingerprint" — what you are</li>
              <li>Focus: accuracy and exact consistency</li>
              <li>Example: "Bob's Plumbing, 123 Main St, (555) 123-4567"</li>
              <li>Lives in: every citation, your website, schema markup</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Citation (the container)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>A specific mention of your NAP online</li>
              <li>A Yelp listing, directory entry, or news mention</li>
              <li>Focus: volume and quality of sources</li>
              <li>Example: A Yelp listing containing your NAP</li>
              <li>Lives in: third-party directories, industry sites</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p>NAP is the information itself; a citation is the container holding that information. Both matter: NAP consistency ensures citations confirm the same entity, and citation volume builds local authority.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for NAP management</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Create a NAP master document.</strong> Write your official business name, address (with unit number and consistent abbreviations), and phone number in one internal document. Copy it character-for-character for every listing. This eliminates the "St" vs "Street" problem at source.</li>
          <li><strong>Add LocalBusiness schema to your website.</strong> Implement JSON-LD LocalBusiness structured data on your homepage and contact page. This tells Google your official NAP in machine-readable format — from your most authoritative source.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix aggregators before individual directories.</strong> Correct Data Axle, Localeze, Foursquare, and Factual first. Their corrections propagate to hundreds of downstream directories automatically, amplifying your effort. Manual corrections on individual directories can be rewritten by aggregator feeds if the aggregator data is wrong.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit citations quarterly.</strong> Use BrightLocal, Moz Local, or Whitespark to scan for inconsistencies every quarter. After any business change — name, location, phone — run an audit immediately and correct within 48 hours to minimise ranking impact duration.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor for and merge duplicate GBP listings.</strong> Duplicate Google Business Profile entries split ranking signals and confuse customers. Review your GBP account and search "[Business Name] + [City]" on Google Maps to find unauthorized duplicates. Request merge or removal through GBP support.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">After a business move or rebrand — act immediately</div>
          <p>The period immediately after a business change is when NAP inconsistency causes the most damage. Old data spreads from aggregator feeds to fresh directory listings while you're still updating. Within 48 hours of any name, address, or phone number change: update GBP, your website schema, the four major aggregators, and your top 20 directories. Do not wait until "things settle."</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common NAP mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Different name formats across platforms</strong> — decide once: legal name, trading name, or DBA. Use it everywhere exactly.</li>
          <li><strong>Updating GBP but forgetting aggregators</strong> — Google Business Profile is one citation. The aggregators feed dozens more. GBP alone is not enough.</li>
          <li><strong>Placing NAP in images or JavaScript</strong> — search engine crawlers cannot read NAP inside images or JavaScript-rendered text. Use crawlable HTML text and supplement with LocalBusiness schema.</li>
          <li><strong>Phone number format variation</strong> — "(555) 123-4567" vs "555-123-4567" vs "+15551234567" can be read as different numbers by citation matching systems. Pick one format and use it everywhere.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring duplicate listings</strong> — duplicate GBP entries split ranking signals. Remove them even if they appear harmless. They are competing against your primary listing.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating NAP as a one-time task</strong> — data aggregators receive business updates from many sources and can rewrite your NAP with old data months after you've corrected it. Quarterly audits are not optional.</li>
        </ul>

